Am I Anti-Woke?Self-Reflection Inspired by Nick Cave, Plus a Taxonomy of Woke, Plus Rattle Bag https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/am-i-anti-woke https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/am-i-anti-wokeIan Leslie Sat, 30 Mar 2024 09:35:57 GMT <div class="captioned-image-container"><figure> <a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3587cd7-2d4c-420c-8040-dedf3d5fa99b_2586x1550.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3587cd7-2d4c-420c-8040-dedf3d5fa99b_2586x1550.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3587cd7-2d4c-420c-8040-dedf3d5fa99b_2586x1550.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3587cd7-2d4c-420c-8040-dedf3d5fa99b_2586x1550.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3587cd7-2d4c-420c-8040-dedf3d5fa99b_2586x1550.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3587cd7-2d4c-420c-8040-dedf3d5fa99b_2586x1550.png" width="1456" height="873" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/a3587cd7-2d4c-420c-8040-dedf3d5fa99b_2586x1550.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:873,&quot;width&quot;:1456,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:5823269,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3587cd7-2d4c-420c-8040-dedf3d5fa99b_2586x1550.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3587cd7-2d4c-420c-8040-dedf3d5fa99b_2586x1550.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3587cd7-2d4c-420c-8040-dedf3d5fa99b_2586x1550.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3587cd7-2d4c-420c-8040-dedf3d5fa99b_2586x1550.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture></div></a> <polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line><figcaption class="image-caption">尼克·凯夫（Nick Cave）参加了查尔斯国王加冕典礼。照片：迪伦·马丁内斯/路透社</figcaption></figure></div><blockquote><p><em><strong>追赶服务：</strong><br><a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/why-its-good-to-be-biased">为什么偏见是好的</a><br><a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/in-praise-of-slow-learners">赞美慢学习者</a><br><a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/the-google-gemini-debacle-shows-us">Google Gemini＆Office Politics</a><br><a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/how-to-fix-dei">如何修复dei</a></em></p></blockquote><p>由于某种原因，我不熟悉尼克·凯夫（Nick Cave）的音乐。我只能唱他的一首歌（<em>在我的怀里</em>），如果您用凯莉（Kylie）算出他的二重奏，则可以唱两首。但是，我喜欢他的<a href="https://www.theredhandfiles.com/">博客文章</a>。他可以为摇滚明星写得很好，确实是作家。我也喜欢阅读他的采访。 <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2024/mar/28/nick-cave-on-love-art-and-the-loss-of-his-sons-its-against-nature-to-bury-your-children">他本周给了《卫报》，</a>在此期间他对“ wokeneses”发表了意见，这促使我反思了自己与它的关系。</p><p> （关于这个词的注释：我不太使用“唤醒”，因为它既充电又模糊不清，但是很多词也是如此，例如“资本主义”，有时我们只需要为缺乏而做<a class="footnote-anchor" data-component-name="FootnoteAnchorToDOM" id="footnote-anchor-2" href="#footnote-2" target="_self">更好</a>的选择<a class="footnote-anchor" data-component-name="FootnoteAnchorToDOM" id="footnote-anchor-1" href="#footnote-1" target="_self">。</a></p><p>像大多数摇滚明星和艺术家一样，Cave是一个左倾的自由主义者，但他的思想富有，从各种影响力中吸取了众多的影响，包括，包括基督教，尽管他不是一个练习的基督徒）。结果，他担任了他的环境不寻常的职位。例如，<a href="https://www.theredhandfiles.com/what-is-mercy-for-you/">他写道</a>，“取消文化”正在“对社会的创造灵魂产生窒息影响”。他在另一篇<a href="https://www.theredhandfiles.com/why-do-you-write/">博客文章</a>中说，他被“唤醒文化”所击退，因为它“缺乏谦卑以及其主张的家长式和教义的叙述”。</p><p>或以他对君主制的态度。澳大利亚人的凯夫（Cave）说，他不是君主制，但他是女王的忠实粉丝（“我见过的最具魅力的女人……她实际上发光了”），他很高兴<a href="https://www.theguardian.com/music/2023/may/03/nick-cave-reveals-inexplicable-attachment-to-british-royals-ahead-of-attending-kings-coronation">参加了查尔斯国王的加冕礼。</a>澳大利亚代表团。我们可以笑着说他正在尝试两种方式，但我对他的立场表示同情。我认为我们的宪法君主制有一个<a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/being-the-queen">很好的理性案例</a>，但我对此的真正依恋是<a href="https://www.theguardian.com/music/2023/may/03/nick-cave-reveals-inexplicable-attachment-to-british-royals-ahead-of-attending-kings-coronation">这里</a>描述的一个洞穴：<br> <em><br>“我想我想说的是，除了关于废除君主制的无限但必要的辩论之外，我还对皇室成员保持了莫名其妙的情感依恋 - 他们的陌生感，整个事件的深切性质完美地反映了英国本身的独特怪异。我只是被那种事情所吸引 - 怪异，奇特，令人震惊的壮观，令人敬畏的令人敬畏的事物。”</em></p><p>凯夫在<a href="https://www.nickcave.com/faith-hope-and-carnage/">他的书中</a>将自己描述为“气质保守的”。 《卫报》采访主要是关于艺术和悲伤的 - 凯夫在过去九年中失去了两个儿子。但是有一段话，面试官向他询问了他自称的保守主义。他给出一个有趣的答案：</p><p> <em>“保守主义在英国很难谈论，因为人们立即想到保守党。但是我确实认为，小核保守主义是对损失有基本理解的人，一种理解，将某些东西倒下很容易，重新建立它是非常困难的。我们有天生的需要撕毁狗屎，而我个人在这方面更加谨慎，而不是它是围绕我的整个政治意识形态。”</em></p><p>这是伯克和奥克沙特的保守主义。用后者的话说：“保守的气质人认为，一个已知的商品不会轻易为一个未知的人投降。”您可以将其称为“损失”（ <a href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-68679510">RIP Daniel Kahneman</a> ）变成了政治，几乎是精神的原则。</p><p>按照大多数保守派的标准，凯夫是一个进步的人，但我以他说他将保守的敏感性与自由主义者结合在一起。这就是尼日利亚小说家<a href="https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/what-the-outspoken-author-chimamanda-ngozi-adichie-told-me-at-dinner-kgm3gtdjw">Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie所说的</a>：“是的，我有一部分，因为我认为应该有一部分人，这是保守的。有些事情我们不想改变。”</p><p>艺术家应该理解这种歧义，因为那是制作伟大艺术的那种空间。思想家也应该得到它，因为良好的思维是由于阿迪奇所描述的内部气质多样性而产生的。但是歧义是不舒服的，这就是为什么凯夫的面试官认为他必须问下一个问题：</p><p><em>他真的是反醒来的吗？ “我们需要解决的世界存在问题的概念，例如社会正义；我完全对此感到沮丧。但是，我不同意用于实现此目标的方法 - 关闭人们，取消人们。缺乏怜悯，缺乏宽恕……所以这很棘手。正确地掌握这个词的问题在于，如果不必加入对它有问题的全部坚果工作，就无法进行讨论。”</em></p><p> Cave给出了不喜欢wok的两个原因。首先，由于其惩罚性道德主义。其次（请参阅他的<a href="https://www.theredhandfiles.com/why-do-you-write/">博客文章</a>），因为他的学说刚度与他依靠创作音乐的开放和好奇的态度相反。糟糕的是缺乏或抑制保守性气质，以及不适合其算法世界观的思想和敏感性的排斥或封闭。</p><p>唤醒的规则是新的。正如有时所声称的那样，它不是常规的左翼自由主义，而是它在过去十年中成为主流的一种突变。甚至<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qaHLd8de6nM">奥巴马也不受欢迎</a>。</p><p> wokeneses至少是一种社会传染性，至少是一组想法 - 很遗憾地这样说，但是“思维病毒”并不是我听过的最不称职的词。它具有使<a href="https://twitter.com/michaelpforan/status/1621130202402390019?lang=en">聪明人说愚蠢的话</a>并降低<a href="https://www.theartnewspaper.com/2021/11/24/tate-britain-director-defends-museum-against-accusations-of-cancelling-hogarth">机构</a>的<a href="https://twitter.com/educationgadfly/status/1647661137239097344">智商</a>的惊人能力。我认为这部分是强调外表的功能，在每个人都在展示的世界中，被认为是在说正确的话，并且容易受到<a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/how-to-stay-calm-in-a-storm">道德化的勒索软件攻击</a>的影响。</p><p>这就是为什么如此多的权力职位的人被动地与之相处的原因。直到最近（这正在发生变化），对于那些不能或不想冒着在公共场合思考的人来说，臭味一直是一个安全的空间。温和派的被动性使少数激进主义者的影响力巨大，而唤醒了最糟糕的方面 - 分裂，替罪羊，<a href="https://twitter.com/VictoriaPeckham/status/1773790695196602598">晦涩</a>，只是它产生的纯粹荒谬性 - 无需检查就蓬勃发展。</p><p>许多唤醒的位置或行为甚至不需要彼此相关，但是它们似乎是在包装架上购买的 -<a href="https://twitter.com/MikeNayna/status/1719525047285744037">买一个，让它们全部免费</a>。它的支持者尽职尽责地使用相同的术语（“公平”，“非殖民化”，“结构性种族主义”等），而无需审问或辩论甚至理解它们。</p><p>简而言之，糟糕的不仅涉及信仰或有争议的命题，还涉及社会行为，语言和思想习惯。如果您要说“这醒了吗？”，我不仅要考虑实质性位置本身，而且要考虑到它的到达和表达方式。</p><p>它涉及故意没有意识到自己的政治假设。像其他意识形态一样 - 左派主义者会说这是关于新自由主义的 - 假装不是一个。 Wake只是为了不公正而站起来！唤醒只是好意！我从<a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2024/jan/20/the-levels-of-attack-are-extraordinary-gary-lineker-on-punditry-podcasts-and-why-he-wont-stop-speaking-his-mind">加里·莱恩克（Gary Lineker）</a>的采访中给你这件无价的段落：</p><blockquote><p><em>没有提示，他问醒来有什么问题。 “我的意思是，唤醒是什么？有良心，有心，有同理心？那是一件坏事？”</em></p></blockquote><p> Lineker是一个左翼人士，在一天的问题上，可以预见，不可判断地采用任何时尚的左翼位置，无论多么微妙或有争议。这本身并不一定会醒来，而是<em>在假装是非政治性的同时</em>这样做的，而只是一种善良，有爱心，站立的家伙 - 是一个标志性的唤醒动作。 Lineker回答的另一个唤醒的方面是，这是一种陈词滥调，具有零变化，讽刺或自我表达。沃克（Wake）是一个没有个体思想的代祷而乱七八糟的脚本。 </p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/am-i-anti-woke?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/am-i-anti-woke?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share"><span>分享</span></a></p><p>那么我该如何回答监护人的问题？我是反击吗？我显然不是<em>专业</em>人士。但是我也不是乔丹·彼得森（Jordan Peterson）。我与狂热的反醒来的坚果相关的洞穴不安。在反击运动中，我观察到我在亲击中中看到的模因和口号的绵羊般的统一性。</p><p> 1924年，切斯特顿（GK Chesterton）写道，世界如何分为保守派和进步主义者：“进步主义者的业务是犯错。保守派的业务是防止纠正错误。”现在，世界正在分为这种二分法的退化版本：唤醒和抗击。您要么是Kamala Harris或Ron DeSantis。您要么是要教孩子的孩子，有183种不同的性别，要么想禁止同性恋婚姻。</p><p>我不喜欢那个二进制的任何一面。不过，我不想说<em>嘿，我只是看到他们的事，不要在我身上贴上标签</em>（尽管是的，但<a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/the-case-for-centrism">我不喜欢在自己身上贴上标签</a>）。我也不想成为那些喜欢说事物“复杂”的崇高灵魂之一，我们应该重视“细微差别”  - 我讨厌的词 - 同时害怕命名最简单的真理，以防他们让读者不高兴。</p><p>我确实认为有一件事是唤醒的，无论多云，我通常都对它的位置和行话和心灵习惯保持警惕。但是，由于我同意的某些事情被集中在它之下，而且由于我只是不喜欢一直喜欢它，所以我不会说我是“反击”。我会说我是“醒来的”。</p><p>实际上，我不信任不会以某种方式醒来的评论员。如果您的工作的一部分是指出伪善和愚蠢，那么您应该避免批评恐怖，因为在许多<a href="https://twitter.com/mrianleslie/status/1583004091088654336">文化</a>和<a href="https://archive.ph/OvUKH">慈善</a>机构中，某些公司在<a href="https://twitter.com/dougponder/status/1635704489406504961">大学</a>中确实普遍存在（在这里反沃克人是正确的）和<a href="https://twitter.com/soniasodha/status/1646058557559787520">政府的部分地区</a>。但这并不需要意味着使用其最无意识的批评家的言论，或者对此变得单狂。 </p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/am-i-anti-woke?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/am-i-anti-woke?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share"><span>分享</span></a></p><p>现在，我们有了唤醒的分类法，或者是一个开始的分类法：亲鲁克，反殴打，醒来。但是我认为，在保罗·格雷厄姆（Paul Graham）关于<a href="https://paulgraham.com/conformism.html">合格四个象限</a>的文章的帮助下，我们可以进一步发展。<br></p><p><a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/am-i-anti-woke">阅读更多</a></p>; 
Why It's Good To Be BiasedWhen everyone is rational, reasonable and nice, we all get a little dimmer https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/why-ist-good-to-be be Be Be Be https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/why-ist-good-to-be be Be Be BeIan Leslie Sat, 23 Mar 2024 09:37:26 GMT <div class="captioned-image-container"><figure> <a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59d7ac07-8147-4d95-a9de-1ebd567e4c5f_499x294.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59d7ac07-8147-4d95-a9de-1ebd567e4c5f_499x294.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59d7ac07-8147-4d95-a9de-1ebd567e4c5f_499x294.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59d7ac07-8147-4d95-a9de-1ebd567e4c5f_499x294.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59d7ac07-8147-4d95-a9de-1ebd567e4c5f_499x294.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59d7ac07-8147-4d95-a9de-1ebd567e4c5f_499x294.png" width="663" height="390.62525050100203" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/59d7ac07-8147-4d95-a9de-1ebd567e4c5f_499x294.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:294,&quot;width&quot;:499,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:663,&quot;bytes&quot;:null,&quot;alt&quot;:&quot;Drunk History | Hankering for History&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:null,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="Drunk History | Hankering for History" title="醉汉|渴望历史" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59d7ac07-8147-4d95-a9de-1ebd567e4c5f_499x294.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59d7ac07-8147-4d95-a9de-1ebd567e4c5f_499x294.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59d7ac07-8147-4d95-a9de-1ebd567e4c5f_499x294.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59d7ac07-8147-4d95-a9de-1ebd567e4c5f_499x294.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture></div></a> <polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line><figcaption class="image-caption">威尔·费雷尔（Will Ferrell）和唐·奇德（Don Cheadle）饰演林肯（Lincoln）和道格拉斯（Douglass）</figcaption></figure></div><blockquote><p><em><strong>追赶服务：</strong><br><a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/in-praise-of-slow-learners">赞美慢学习者</a><br><a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/the-state-of-the-culture-isnot-bad">文化的状态是……还不错</a><br><a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/the-google-gemini-debacle-shows-us">Google Gemini＆Office Politics</a><br><a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/how-to-fix-dei">如何修复dei</a></em></p></blockquote><p>生孩子的令人不安的事情之一是，他们揭露了您无知的可怕深度。他们有一个习惯，问“法国大革命是什么？”之类的问题。您踏上一个充满信心的答案，然后到第三句话结束时，您会感觉像是<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ipV2u-MxlFc&amp;t=163s">醉酒的历史</a>视频中的某人。至少，我愿意。</p><p>被要求解释某些事情通常会揭示您认为自己所知道的知识和实际所知道的东西之间的差距 - 大多数时候，我们在不足或忽略的情况下都存在差距。心理学家称这是“<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Illusion_of_explanatory_depth">解释性深度的幻想</a>”。在实验中，他们问人们是否知道自行车的工作方式，拉链或厕所。受访者说，当然我们不是白痴。但是，当被要求用文字或图表解释时，它们会产生混乱的混乱。</p><p>每当我看到反以色列抗议者对冲突的最基本问题<a href="https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2023/11/09/protesters-pro-palestine-march-not-sure-hamas-invade-israel/">而陷入困境</a>时，我都会想起这种效果。实际上，我们的许多政治话语都发生在人们的想法或觉得自己所知道的以及他们实际做的事情之间的差距中。倒入那个差距中，响了很多噪音和愤怒。</p><p><a href="https://www.conspicuouscognition.com/p/in-politics-the-truth-is-not-self">哲学家丹·威廉姆斯（Dan Williams）</a>说，当涉及政治时，许多人是“天真的现实主义者”  - 也就是说，他们倾向于认为他们看到了自己在客观，清晰，清晰，清晰，全面地看待任何事物的现实，几乎没有或没有有意识地意识到自己的无知或感知扭曲。</p><p>他列举了沃尔特·利普曼（Walter Lippman），他是二十世纪伟大的关于民主的思想家之一：“对手必须始终被解释，而我们所寻求的最后解释是他看到了一系列不同的事实。”威廉姆斯认为天真的现实主义是非常有害的，这是民主的问题：</p><blockquote><p><em>因为人们是天真的现实主义者，所以他们倾向于认为政治问题的解决方案是不言而喻的。这导致了许多不良政治，并为煽动者提供了普遍的支持，他们承诺通过“明显的”政策强迫。此外，如果真理是不言而喻的，那么否认真相的人必须是骗子，愚蠢或疯狂。</em></p></blockquote><p>然后，他继续概述了一些有趣的假设，即即使被指出并批评我像他这样的明智的人，为什么天真的现实主义仍然存在。对于Ruffian读者来说，知道我对他的漂移表示同情，这对Ruffian读者来说并不奇怪。我确实认为，如果某些人对自己的政治信仰不确定，并且更渴望参与您所说的自我感受主义，那么公众话语将有所改善。</p><p>一般而言，人们对复杂的政策问题或冲突的了解越多，对解决方案的确定性就越少。为了一个令人钦佩的例子，<a href="https://simplecast.econtalk.org/episodes/voices-from-gaza-with-ahmed-alkhatib">请听艾哈迈德·阿尔卡蒂布（Ahmed Alkhatib）在这场战争中被以色列人杀害和流离失所的艾哈迈德·阿尔卡蒂布（Ahmed Alkhatib）</a> ，并且比我们每天听到的任何活动家或记者更了解地面上的情况。他不会妖魔化以色列人或重复口号或提出“停火”等便利解决方案。他知道太多。</p><p>说了这么多，我认为我们并不希望<em>每个人</em>都对自己的信念无可挑剔或具有完全校准的<a href="https://www.cnbc.com/2021/06/03/the-type-of-confidence-jeff-bezos-has-and-why-it-makes-you-more-likable.html">认知信心</a>。在任何给定的人（一个社会，团队，家庭）中，它有助于结合认知风格和气质（我上次在<a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/in-praise-of-slow-learners">我的文章</a>第二部分中谈到了这一主题）。对于我们所有人来说，让我们中的一些人过度自信是一件好事。</p><p>当丹说，天真现实主义者更有可能采取政治行动时，他谈到了一个可能的原因。我们当中那些担心我们对以色列加沙不太了解的人不太了解真正的观点，这并不是可能改变辩论的条款的人。也许这是一个糟糕的例子，但是选择您钦佩的政治成就，您会发现Naive Realism在某个阶段至关重要。政治的目的是改变世界，而不是做出理性的判断。</p><p>我对非理性的美德感兴趣。在<a href="https://ian-leslie.com/conflicted">冲突/如何分歧</a>我写的关于确认偏见的上行方面，通常被认为是人类推理中的悲惨缺陷。进化心理学家丹·斯佩伯（Dan Sperber）和雨果·梅塞尔（Hugo Mercier）认为，这是一个特征，而不是人类认知的障碍，因为它增加了个人渴望产生新信息并提出更好的论点的愿望。</p><p>考虑一下当某人与您矛盾时的情况。您真的想考虑自己正确的所有原因以及另一个人为什么错的原因，尤其是如果这是您关心的问题。您可能是出于自私或情感原因这样做的 - 证明自己是合理的或证明自己的聪明程度 - 但是即使如此，您可能对参数和信息的贡献比其他众多的贡献要多。</p><p>如果一方或双方立即让另一方交给另一方，那么您将无法有富有成效的观点交流。实际上，有点过分自信，有点热，甚至有些不合理（不走得太远），这可能会有所帮助。情感的功能是激励。当我将自己最好的游戏带到桌子上并带上自己的桌子时，出现的答案将因在我们分歧的坩埚中锻造而变得更加强大。</p><p>实际上 - 在这里，我将要在深处，因为这是我对所有事物的宏伟理论 - 最有生产力的社会系统（组织，社会等）是由<em>某种</em>无知，有偏见，封闭的特工组成的（个人或群体），几乎对所有其他代理人都足够开放，可以学习和发展。太雾化了，以及系统的萎缩；过于连接，每个代理都变得不那么独特，从而使隐喻的表不足，从而导致缺乏多样性好处的系统。</p><p>进度是由（WHO）独立但相互联系的代理人驱动的，并且在忽略这些条件中的任何一个时都会受到阻碍。从个人到团队再到社会，您都会看到这种效果一直升高。科学和历史有一些很好的例子。</p><div><hr></div><p><em>跳跃后，更多关于这种动态的工作方式以及嘎嘎声袋的更多信息，其中包括：</em></p><ul><li><p><em>如何使用AI写作</em></p></li><li><p><em>关于哈马斯伤亡人数的统计怀疑论</em></p></li><li><p><em>是否存在生物种族？</em> （剧透：是）</p></li><li><p><em>一些快乐而动人的音乐</em></p></li><li><p><em>气候变化的好消息</em></p></li><li><p><em><strong>如果您尚未取出付费订阅，那么现在是时候了。这很简单，它的价值很高，这就是使Ruffian成为可能的原因。谢谢你！</strong></em> </p></li></ul><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/why-its-good-to-be-biased?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/why-its-good-to-be-biased?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share"><span>分享</span></a></p><p></p><p><a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/why-its-good-to-be-biased">阅读更多</a></p>; 
In Praise of Slow LearnersHow the Tortoise Beats the Hare https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/in-praise-of-slow-learners https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/in-praise-of-slow-learnersIan Leslie Sat, 16 Mar 2024 08:14:31 GMT <div class="captioned-image-container"><figure> <a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7798eb08-9d55-46a2-a5ab-d84e16ff22a2_2560x1536.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7798eb08-9d55-46a2-a5ab-d84e16ff22a2_2560x1536.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7798eb08-9d55-46a2-a5ab-d84e16ff22a2_2560x1536.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7798eb08-9d55-46a2-a5ab-d84e16ff22a2_2560x1536.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7798eb08-9d55-46a2-a5ab-d84e16ff22a2_2560x1536.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7798eb08-9d55-46a2-a5ab-d84e16ff22a2_2560x1536.jpeg" width="1456" height="874" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/7798eb08-9d55-46a2-a5ab-d84e16ff22a2_2560x1536.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:874,&quot;width&quot;:1456,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:null,&quot;alt&quot;:&quot;Startup lessons from the tortoise &amp; the hare: start slower to finish faster  - thestartupfactory.tech&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:null,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="Startup lessons from the tortoise &amp; the hare: start slower to finish faster  - thestartupfactory.tech" title="乌龟和野兔的启动课程：启动较慢以更快地完成-TATARTUPFACTORY.TECH" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7798eb08-9d55-46a2-a5ab-d84e16ff22a2_2560x1536.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7798eb08-9d55-46a2-a5ab-d84e16ff22a2_2560x1536.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7798eb08-9d55-46a2-a5ab-d84e16ff22a2_2560x1536.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7798eb08-9d55-46a2-a5ab-d84e16ff22a2_2560x1536.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture></div></a> <polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line><figcaption class="image-caption">照片：GK Vikki Hart。版权所有：盖蒂图片社</figcaption></figure></div><blockquote><p><em><strong>追赶服务：</strong><br><a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/the-state-of-the-culture-isnot-bad">文化的状态是……还不错</a><br><a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/the-google-gemini-debacle-shows-us">Google Gemini＆Office Politics</a><br><a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/how-to-fix-dei">如何修复dei</a></em></p></blockquote><p><br>在他的<a href="https://www.penguin.co.uk/articles/2022/11/murakami-writing-process-novelist-as-a-vocation">写作小说练习的书中，</a>村上村里讲述了一个故事，讲述了两个男人，其中一名非常聪明，另一个人却少了，他们去富士山去看看所有的大惊小怪。他们站在底部，凝视着。聪明的人会细微地转移到不同的有利位置，专心地扫描山脉，处理有关地形和方面的信息。他说：“现在我看到了什么使它如此特别。”</p><p>不太聪明的人无法像这样弄清楚。所以他留在后面，爬上山。他花了很多时间和努力。到他到达山顶时，他已经筋疲力尽了。但是现在他了解他的朋友没有的方式。</p><p>穆拉卡米说，小说家往往就像这两个男人的愚蠢者。他们是<em>效率低下的学习者</em>。他们无法快速或轻松地弄清楚事情，或者至少他们觉得自己不可能。他们没有抽象思想的理想设施。他们依靠混凝土和感性来弄清世界。他们一次爬山，一次一个细节。他写道：“以我的看法，有才华的人并不特别适合写小说……小说的写作或讲故事的讲述是一种以缓慢的速度进行的活动，所以说话。”</p><p>像很多人一样，我希望比我更聪明。与某些人不同，这不是我担心的事情。我年轻时会更担心它，但是现在我根据压倒性的证据来接受，有很多人 - 包括朋友，同事，我的妻子，他们 - 毫无疑问地更多比我聪明，这就是事实。这些人比我更成功地吸收和保留信息。比我更快地了解新游戏或语言的规则；更加敏捷，语音流利。</p><p>我也很方便地看到，成为一个相对较慢的学习者有一定的优势。现在，我不会争辩说这些优势大于缺点。如果有机会升级，我会订购更快，更强大的大脑。但是我建议我们高估快速学习并低估了缓慢的学习，因为我们倾向于将所有认知任务视为冲刺，从一开始就可以尽可能快地跑步。生活中的许多任务更像是长距离跑步，在这里慢慢进行以减少比赛时间的速度。小说写作是一个（村上本人是敬业的马拉松赛跑者）。</p><p>缓慢的学习者比快速学习者具有隐藏的优势：他们必须学习自适应策略才能跟上更聪明的同龄人，从长远来看，这些策略可以证明非常有价值 - 因此有时慢慢学习者超越了他们的同龄人。</p><p>基普·索恩（Kip Thorne）是2017年诺贝尔重力物理学奖的共同获奖者。您会想象这样的人总是感觉像房间里最聪明的人。但是，当索恩在1950年代首次到达加利福尼亚理工学院（加州理工学院）时，他挣扎着：“第一年很难；我的思想没有像其他学生那样快。”他说。 “我意识到要生存，我必须制定策略来补偿。”</p><p>在<a href="https://www.alumni.caltech.edu/awardees/2015-5-18-kip-s-thorne-bs-62">我引用的采访</a>中，他没有指定这些策略是什么，但我们可以猜到。也许他比其他人更努力地工作，并更深入地思考，探讨了他的同学会找到解决方案的问题，坚持不懈地坚持下去，直到他从头开始理解他们。也许他也外侧思考了他们，以其他学生甚至没有考虑的方式，或者他从相邻知识领域进行了学习。但是他这样做了，索恩不得不沿着自己的路线爬上山，而这样做，他超出了他更快的学习同学的成就。</p><p>当然，这种策略也是一种智力的形式。技术人员和作家Nabeel Qureshi<a href="https://nabeelqu.co/understanding">在有关理解本质的文章中</a>，区分了智力的“硬件”和“软件”。快速学习者拥有的是卓越的硬件 - 原始处理能力，大型内存能力。 But slow learners can sometimes outflank fast learners, intellectually, if they have superior software: character traits like honesty, bravery, and humility, and behaviour traits like curiosity and persistence.</p><p> The good thing about these traits - it might better to think of them as habits - is that they are elastic. Even if there is a genetic component to them, they can be learned, practiced, developed. Note that this is an argument for putting yourself in rooms with people who are faster learners than you. When you come up against people with better hardware you&#39;re strongly incentivised to develop your software, in order to match or better your peers and competitors.</p><p> If there are traits that can make dimmer people smarter, the converse is also true. One of the pitfalls faced by fast learners is that they are not incentivised to develop their software. Really clever people get a lot of feedback early on in life that they are, well, really clever. As they get older, they discount information that suggests they haven&#39;t understood something and over-weight information that suggests they have. Consequently, they can become gradually stupid.</p><p> Charlie Munger: “A lot of smart people think they&#39;re way smarter than they are, and therefore they do worse than dumb people. And it&#39;s very common to be utterly brilliant and think you&#39;re way the hell smarter than you are.&quot; ( <a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/marginal-stupidity">I wrote about this effect in 2022</a> after Liz Truss and Kwasi Kwarteng crashed the British economy. Politics rewards fast learners right up until those fast learners fail spectacularly.) Slow learners are less likely to fall prey to this trap, since they&#39;re more used to getting and noticing feedback which tells them they&#39;re not so smart.</p><p> Nabeel Qureshi is particularly interested in the “will to understand” - the dogged refusal to accept superficial answers, the desire to go further and deeper in the search for truth. That is a slow learning trait - it literally slows you down - and much about the education system and professional world militates against it. You can mechanically perform calculus operations without ever deeply understanding calculus, and in fact that&#39;s what you&#39;re encouraged to do at school, since nobody has time for your questions; just do what you need to pass the exam. At work, once you learn the tricks of making an impressive presentation, you stop pushing yourself to really understand what you&#39;re presenting.没时间了。</p><p> Speed kills understanding. The secret of improving your intelligence, and your judgement, is knowing when to choose the slow route; when to look at the primary data yourself rather than accept a second or fifth-hand summary of it; when to take three months to read one great book rather than trying to read twenty mediocre ones; when to admit that you haven&#39;t grasped a problem, rather than generating a plausible but superficial take on it; when to ask the stupid question that everyone&#39;s wondering about but nobody wants to verbalise; when to push those around you or just yourself to more precisely define what you&#39;re arguing about.</p><p> Slow learners are more likely to do things the hard way, because they haven&#39;t been pampered by their own brain. They&#39;re very familiar with the feeling of not-understanding, and have learned to welcome it as a spur.</p><p> In short, those of us who are slow learners needn&#39;t be embarrassed about it. We may not understand things as quickly as some, but the habit of conscious not-understanding is a valuable one to have. It can be very productive to dwell, even revel, in incomprehension.</p><p> Somebody who understands this is James H. Simons. Simons received his doctorate in mathematics at 23 and taught the subject at Harvard and Princeton, while working as a code breaker for the US National Security Agency. Later he won geometry&#39;s highest prize, before founding Renaissance Technologies, one of the world&#39;s most successful hedge funds. Now he focuses on his philanthropic efforts, which include training and funding maths teachers.</p><p> In a <em>New York Times</em> <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/08/science/a-billionaire-mathematicians-life-of-ferocious-curiosity.html?_r=0">profile of him from 2014</a> , when he was 76, what shines through is the profound delight and solace Simons takes in thinking - in thinking long, hard, and slow. “I wasn&#39;t the fastest guy in the world,” he says, looking back on his youth. “I wouldn&#39;t have done well in an Olympiad or a math contest. But I like to ponder. And pondering things, just sort of thinking about it and thinking about it, turns out to be a pretty good approach.” </p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/in-praise-of-slow-learners?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/in-praise-of-slow-learners?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share"><span>分享</span></a></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.ian-leslie.com/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/subscribe?"><span>现在订阅</span></a></p><p><em><strong>This is Part I. In Part II, after the jump, I look the virtues of slow learning in the context of teams and organisations, personal relationships, and AI.</strong></em></p><p><a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/in-praise-of-slow-learners">阅读更多</a></p>; 
The State of the Culture Is...Not Bad, ActuallyReflections on a good year for the Oscars https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/the-state-of-the-culture-isnot-bad https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/the-state-of-the-culture-isnot-badIan Leslie Sat, 09 Mar 2024 08:36:59 GMT <div class="captioned-image-container"><figure> <a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff3baef48-2efd-45da-82e5-9899a002cd04_1000x562.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff3baef48-2efd-45da-82e5-9899a002cd04_1000x562.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff3baef48-2efd-45da-82e5-9899a002cd04_1000x562.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff3baef48-2efd-45da-82e5-9899a002cd04_1000x562.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff3baef48-2efd-45da-82e5-9899a002cd04_1000x562.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff3baef48-2efd-45da-82e5-9899a002cd04_1000x562.png" width="1000" height="562" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f3baef48-2efd-45da-82e5-9899a002cd04_1000x562.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:562,&quot;width&quot;:1000,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:null,&quot;alt&quot;:&quot;Where to Watch the 2024 Oscar Nominated Movies&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:null,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="Where to Watch the 2024 Oscar Nominated Movies" title="Where to Watch the 2024 Oscar Nominated Movies" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff3baef48-2efd-45da-82e5-9899a002cd04_1000x562.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff3baef48-2efd-45da-82e5-9899a002cd04_1000x562.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff3baef48-2efd-45da-82e5-9899a002cd04_1000x562.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff3baef48-2efd-45da-82e5-9899a002cd04_1000x562.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture></div></a> <polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line><figcaption class="image-caption"> Image via <a href="https://variety.com/lists/where-to-watch-2024-oscar-nominated-movies-streaming/">Variety</a> .</figcaption></figure></div><blockquote><p> <em><strong>Catch-up service:</strong><br> <a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/delusional-self-belief-is-a-superpower">On Delusional Self-Belief In Politicians</a><br> <a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/the-google-gemini-debacle-shows-us">Google Gemini &amp; Office Politics</a><br> <a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/how-to-fix-dei">How To Fix DEI</a><br> <a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/the-struggle-to-be-human">The Struggle To Be Human</a></em></p></blockquote><p> Hollywood seems to be undergoing a mini-renaissance. I can&#39;t remember the last Oscars weekend with so many shortlisted films I&#39;ve seen; films I made the effort to go and see at the cinema and didn&#39;t walk out of before the end. And I&#39;m not alone: part of the reason I went to so many is that I wanted to be part of the conversations people were having about them.</p><p> For a long time now we&#39;ve been hearing, and no doubt will continue to hear, that the dominance of the blockbuster franchise has destroyed the kind of movies which traditionally win Oscars: grown-up films with artistic ambitions, telling emotionally nuanced stories without superheroes or the extensive use of CGI. Well, it hasn&#39;t seemed like that from where I&#39;ve been sitting.</p><p> From the Best Picture shortlist, I&#39;ve seen <em>Oppenheimer,</em> <em>American Fiction, The Zone of Interest, Poor Things, Anatomy of a Fall, Maestro, Killers of the Flower Moon.</em> As regular readers will know, I didn&#39;t like all of these equally, but they all explore complex themes with intelligence and wit. They did pretty well with audiences, too, albeit not on the scale of blockbusters ( <em>Oppenheimer</em> aside). Add the two shortlisted movies I haven&#39;t seen, <em>Past Lives</em> and <em>The Holdovers</em> , plus films that just missed out on the shortlist, like <em>All of Us Strangers</em> , and you have a surprisingly long list of “movies they don&#39;t make anymore” 。</p><p> Don&#39;t worry, I&#39;m not getting carried away. The biggest grossing films of 2023 were <a href="https://www.boxofficemojo.com/year/world/2023/">mostly blockbuster franchises</a> . Moviegoing overall has not yet recovered from the pandemic. But this year&#39;s bounty of decent films has given me a little hope that the cultural entropy we seem to be experiencing is reversible, if only temporarily.</p><p> Fellow Substacker Ted Gioia recently argued, in a very popular post called <a href="https://www.honest-broker.com/p/the-state-of-the-culture-2024">&#39;The State of the Culture, 2024&#39;</a> , that the whole of mainstream culture is in inexorable decline, as the “dopamine cartel” of tech companies feed us ever shorter and more meaningless hits of content, both creating and feeding our insatiable need for novelty. Art has been swallowed by Entertainment has been swallowed by Distraction has been swallowed by Addiction.</p><p> Since Ted makes his argument with such force (this is the culmination of arguments he&#39;s been making for years) it&#39;s easy to be seduced, if that&#39;s the word, by his blistering pessimism. But just a little reflection reveals it to be premature.</p><p> For instance, book sales have been <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2023/may/31/bloomsbury-reports-sales-surge-people-buy-books-affordable-diversion">pretty robust</a> (with a lot of sales driven by evil TikTok). TV drama is still more artistically interesting than it was in the twentieth century, and if anything shows have become <em>too</em> long and complex, rather than being reduced to thirty second dopamine triggers <a class="footnote-anchor" data-component-name="FootnoteAnchorToDOM" id="footnote-anchor-1" href="#footnote-1" target="_self">1</a> .</p><p> While we may not be in a golden age of popular music, there&#39;s a vast amount of very good and interesting stuff out there, probably more than ever; <a href="https://www.honest-broker.com/p/the-100-best-recordings-of-2023-part">Ted himself</a> seems to find hundreds of albums to enjoy every year. In classical music, concert-going hasn&#39;t recovered from 2020, but in terms of new recordings it&#39;s in <a href="https://marginalrevolution.com/marginalrevolution/2023/12/my-classical-music-listening-for-the-year.html">surprisingly good shape</a> .</p><p> When it comes to film, I would agree that until this last year, excellence seemed thin on the ground. We&#39;re obviously nowhere near the artistic peaks of the 1970s. But that doesn&#39;t mean it&#39;s been downhill all the way. </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2cb9da49-a7c1-4328-a996-cdc2048f7fe8_1592x1150.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2cb9da49-a7c1-4328-a996-cdc2048f7fe8_1592x1150.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2cb9da49-a7c1-4328-a996-cdc2048f7fe8_1592x1150.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2cb9da49-a7c1-4328-a996-cdc2048f7fe8_1592x1150.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2cb9da49-a7c1-4328-a996-cdc2048f7fe8_1592x1150.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2cb9da49-a7c1-4328-a996-cdc2048f7fe8_1592x1150.png" width="588" height="424.84615384615387" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2cb9da49-a7c1-4328-a996-cdc2048f7fe8_1592x1150.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:1052,&quot;width&quot;:1456,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:588,&quot;bytes&quot;:null,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:null,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2cb9da49-a7c1-4328-a996-cdc2048f7fe8_1592x1150.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2cb9da49-a7c1-4328-a996-cdc2048f7fe8_1592x1150.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2cb9da49-a7c1-4328-a996-cdc2048f7fe8_1592x1150.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2cb9da49-a7c1-4328-a996-cdc2048f7fe8_1592x1150.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption"> via the excellent <a href="https://www.statsignificant.com/p/whats-the-greatest-year-in-oscar">Stat Significant</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> This chart shows films on Oscars shortlists that still show up in critics&#39; &#39;Best Ever&#39; lists. It&#39;s a proxy for the quality of films being made in each decade. Yes, one bar towers impressively over the rest. It wasn&#39;t just that the decade of bell-bottoms and oil crises produced so many enduringly great films, it&#39;s that the great films were commercially successful. <a href="https://www.the-numbers.com/market/1975/top-grossing-movies">In 1975,</a> the top ten grossing films included <em>One Flew Over the Cuckoo&#39;s Nest</em> , <em>Shampoo</em> , and <em>Dog Day Afternoon</em> .</p><p> <em>Jaws</em> was number one that year. While undeniably a great movie, its huge success was also, at least if you&#39;re an extreme movie snob, the beginning of the end for Hollywood film as an art form; that or <em>Star War</em> s, from a couple of years later. These two films spawned the blockbuster.</p><p> But what&#39;s most striking to me about this chart is that it shows how that decade - the 1970s - was an outlier. Note that this graph has no curve or slope on either side of its peak. There&#39;s no linear trend. Take out that freakishly tall bar and you see that the number of enduringly great films per decade bobs around a mean.</p><p> The 1970s wholly deserves its &#39;golden age&#39; status. It&#39;s interesting to think about why a creative industry hits that kind of streak. The most eloquent explanation I&#39;ve seen is from Adam Gopnik, who made it in an essay <a href="https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/12/28/the-mixed-up-masters-of-early-animation">on the early days of Disney</a> :</p><blockquote><p> <em>The larger story of the intersection of commerce and the popular arts, within which this history sits, is not a wholly negative one, but it does have a specific shape. <strong>High moments in popular art begin when no one has cracked the commercial code sufficiently to know what will work…and a proliferation of possibilities becomes available, including, above all, the possibility of open-ended, unkempt emotion.</strong> This proliferation of possibilities happened with pop music in the late sixties, with American film in the early seventies, with long-form television in the first decade of this century.</em> <a class="footnote-anchor" data-component-name="FootnoteAnchorToDOM" id="footnote-anchor-2" href="#footnote-2" target="_self">2</a> <em>A receptive audience, a plurality of artists, and the basic commercial uncertainty about what works or what can be made to work, and, presto, you get “Sgt. Pepper” and “The Godfather”; then someone cracks the code of commerce, and you get “Frampton Comes Alive!” and “Smokey and the Bandit.”</em> [My emphasis].</p></blockquote><p> A little harsh on <em>Frampton Comes Alive</em> perhaps, but you get the idea. Golden ages for commercial art forms happen in windows of transition. Take a mature industry, find a bunch of hungry young creatives who are really into what they do - who see it as a vocation rather than just a job - add a sense of profound uncertainty about what works in the marketplace, and boom.</p><p> As Adam notes, this works well as a description of Hollywood in the 1970s. If you&#39;ve read <em><a href="https://www.amazon.co.uk/Easy-Riders-Raging-Bulls-Sex-drugs/dp/0747544212">Easy Riders, Raging Bulls</a></em> , you&#39;ll know that this golden age was born from desperation. Consumers were staying home to watch TV rather than going to the cinema, and the old studio system was crumbling. Ageing executives had no handle on a generation of kids who had grown up with rock music, mass protests, and drug culture.</p><p> So the suits threw the car keys to a cohort of headstrong young film geeks - Coppola, Scorsese, Spielberg, Lucas, Nicolson, De Niro - and let them drive. The result was a lot of thematically and formally adventurous movies, overflowing with unkempt emotion, some of which made a ton of money. <em>The Godfather</em> and its sequel were the most successful movies of their respective years (1972 and 1975). But these artists were erratic, and so was their work, and commerce thrives on consistency. It wasn&#39;t until after <em>Jaws</em> and <em>Star Wars</em> showed the way that the code was cracked, and the artistic window began to close.</p><p> Of course, hits were still hard to predict and there remained a lot of <a href="https://www.the-numbers.com/market/1993/top-grossing-movies">quality and a lot of surprises in the movies that</a> followed. It wasn&#39;t until the rise of the Marvel Cinematic Universe in this century that Hollywood really found a formula for consistent success, at which point the creative horizons of the industry shrank considerably. But now that even <a href="https://archive.ph/cgZ0C">the MCU is in decline</a> , a new period of profound instability beckons, made more perilous by the tech-driven trends Gioia identifies. Perhaps this year&#39;s Oscar movies represent the first fruits of that uncertainty.</p><p> Look, I would not want to make a strong argument that any of our art forms are in rude health. <a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/the-struggle-to-be-human">I might even agree</a> that we&#39;re in some kind of broad, long-term creative decline driven by the <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2024/01/09/podcasts/transcript-ezra-klein-interviews-kyle-chayka.html">algorithmic flattening</a> of everything. But our culture is too variegated and perverse to be move in a straight line, in <em>any</em> direction. Even if the river is flowing down the mountain, there will be twists and eddies and changes of course - and from time to time, water might even flow uphill. </p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/the-state-of-the-culture-isnot-bad?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/the-state-of-the-culture-isnot-bad?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share"><span>分享</span></a></p><div><hr></div><p><strong>The Ruffian is reader-supported, with free and paid subscriptions available. If you&#39;d like to support my work the best way is to take up a paid subscription. You&#39;ll also get the best experience of the Ruffian that way.干杯!</strong> </p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.ian-leslie.com/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/subscribe?"><span>现在订阅</span></a></p><div><hr></div><p><em>After the jump:</em></p><ul><li><p> <em>A young woman who&#39;s trying to solve the problems of old age.</em></p></li><li><p> <em>A fascinating academic study on why elites misread public opinion.</em></p></li><li><p> <em>Thoughts on Biden post-SOTU</em></p></li><li><p> <em>My personal 2024 Oscar awards</em></p></li><li><p> <em>A beautiful song from 2023…and more.</em></p></li></ul><p><a href="https://www.ian-leslie.com/p/the-state-of-the-culture-isnot-bad">阅读更多</a></p>;
